</center>

<code>void setup() {
size(750, 300);
}
void draw() {
background(204);
line(width/2, height/2, mouseX, mouseY);
}
</code>

After learning how to write into the console I then went on to learn how to map mouse movement to change something on the screen. After making a 750px x 300px canvas I then added a line. This line starts at the centre of the canvas as the height and width are split in half. Then the other end of the line is mapped to mouseX and mouseY. This means when I move the mouse around the canvas the other end of the line is attached to the mouse. This experiment was pretty simple, but it shows that I could possibly change the mouse to something else later on and make it attach to a colour or object on a camera.

[video width="750" height="300" autoplay="autoplay" loop="loop" webm="http://www.matthewlean.co.uk/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Mousefollow.webm"][/video]

After learning how the basic layout worked I wanted to create a simple drawing code. After seeing many examples of complex drawing sketches online I wanted to start my way towards creating something more complex. I first however wanted to make this, so started with a similar void setup and then went on to the draw. This section allowed me to choose the properties of the ellipse and were and how they are made. The two if statements allow both mouse click and right mouse click to be used. With right mouse click being a clear button, which makes the background back to the default value and so clearing all the paint on the canvas. Mouse pressed it set to the X and Y values of the mouse and given a size of 20x20px. This means that every time the mouse is pressed every second 60 ellipses should be drawn.

<code>
void setup() {
size(750, 450);
background(#CDCBCD);
frameRate(60);
}
<code>
void draw() {
stroke(255);
smooth(8);
if (mousePressed) {
ellipse(mouseX, mouseY, 20,20);
}
if (mouseButton==RIGHT) {
background(#CDCBCD);
}
}
</code>

[video width="750" height="450" autoplay="autoplay" loop="loop" webm="http://www.matthewlean.co.uk/blog/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/simpledraw.webm"][/video]

<code>
void setup() {
size(992, 558);
background(#CDCBCD);
frameRate(60);
smooth(100);
}
void draw() {
stroke(random(255));
color(random(200));
smooth(8);
if (mousePressed) {
ellipse(mouseX+random(-100), mouseY+random(-100),5,5);
}
if (mouseButton==RIGHT) {
saveFrame("blog_4.jpg");
}
}</code>

As soon as I created a single circle I thought of how more than one could give more interest to the brush. If the shape and dispersion of the circles changed a textured brush could be shown. I then decided to make many random small ellipses appear when the left mouse button is pressed. This random value would provide a more interesting layout than one I could create. I also changed the right button press to a saveFrame value. This would give me a .jpg whenever I pressed the right mouse. This could also be set with every frame and could be used to make a short animation.

<img src="http://www.matthewlean.co.uk/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/dots.jpg" alt="dots" width="750" height="auto" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-109" />

After this we learned how to rotate the canvas and produce circular patterns. This is achieved by a repeated draw of a shape rotated around the centre point (width/2,height/2). I also used integers in this sketch, allowing me to apply calculations and make values of rotation and repetition. After making this sketch I applied a noStroke to remove the lines around the outside of the ellipses. This gave a much cleaner look to the pattern. I also made the fill increase to give a rainbow colour to the pattern as it progresses. This steady increase gives a smoother look to the animation.

<code>
void setup() {
size(750,750);
colorMode(HSB,100);
smooth();
noStroke();
}
int rotation=0;
int el=0;
int h=0;
void draw() {
fill(245,10);
rect(0,0,width,height);
translate(width/2,height/2);
rotate(rotation);
fill(h,100,100,25);
ellipse(el,el,el,el);
rotation=rotation+90;
el=(el+1)%150;
h=(h+1)%100;
}
</code>

