Well you could probably ask processing that, and you can. The time when you think about it is very complex to code. Depending on what time zone you are in the time is different, similarly depending what time of the year and if it’s a leap year it’s also different. So when I first heard we were going to learn how to make a clock in processing I was looking forward to lots and lots of code. Luckily this code and these many additions and occurrences have been done before so it’s actually not that hard.

First we start with a normal void setup and then add some integers. These are the give the values of the hour minute second…
<code>
int h=hour();
int m=minute();
int s=second();
int y=year();
int mo=month();
int d=day();
</code>

Then after this in the draw section we just input these values in and add some colour to the background (fill) and maybe even change the font. I also then have to place the text on the x and y coordinates so they are in order. After this I have a working digital clock sketch.

However this isn’t that interesting so I decided I could make it a little bit more interesting, I remembered a website I had seen a white ago and went searching. http://whatcolourisit.scn9a.org/ is a website which shows the Hex colour at that time, so as an example at three forty in the afternoon (15:40:00) the hex value would be #154000. I thought this was an interesting concept and decided I would do the same but inside processing. I then just used the int value for the seconds and input that into the first value of the background colour.

<code>
background(s,100,100); 
</code>

The result shows a bright background throughout the whole minute, this was what I was after as using the hours and days took too long and meant that the average viewer to the site wouldn’t see the whole colour spectrum and the change of colour I wanted to show.

<iframe width="778" height="480" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" src="http://www.openprocessing.org/sketch/181641/embed/?width=750&height=400&border=true"></iframe>

After this I wanted to make something a bit more strange and complex. I chose to add a translate and rotate to the sketch. This rotation was on the rectangles which I added and the text as well. I set the length of the second hand to the number of the second, and also used the other values for hour and minutes. I did spend a lot of time trying to get it just right however what I came up with is in my eyes much funnier. The clock is almost unreadable after it is left to run for a few minutes and as the layers build up you are just left with a mass of colour as the change is so slight and takes hours.. (Literally). Overall I may come back to this at a later date and make this clock again, but for now I enjoy my messy unreadable clock.

<iframe width="778" height="830" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" src="http://www.openprocessing.org/sketch/181688/embed/?width=750&height=750&border=true"></iframe>

<code>
void setup(){
size(750,750);
frameRate(1);
colorMode(HSB,100);
}
int rotation=0;
void draw(){
translate(width/2,height/2);
fill(#000000);
rotation=rotation+6;
rotate(rotation);
//set the variables up for the time and date
int h=hour();
int m=minute();
int s=second();
int y=year();
int mo=month();
int d=day();
textSize(30);
stroke(0,0,0);
strokeWeight(0);
//Display Seconds
textSize(20);text(s,s*4,20,20);
fill(s,100,100);
rect(0,0,s*4,10);
//Display Minutes
textSize(30);
fill(m+s,100,100);
rect(0,20,m+200,10);
text(m,m+220,40,30);
//Display Hours
textSize(40);
fill(h+s,100,100);
rect(0,40,h+300,10);
text(h,h+300,50,50);
}
</code>

Using a webcam in processing allows me to make a sketch much more accessible and interactive than a mouse based interactive sketch. This allows the users to just walk in-front of the camera and see the effects produced by processing on the screen. For my project in processing we were tasked into creating an interactive piece that will be placed in the lobby area of the building.

When researching the area I found out that most of the people who move through the area do not stay for long. Most people make a direct route through the area to get to their classes and do not take that much interest into what is on the screens or on the walls in the room. This meant that making something that was very interactive and took time to explain was pretty much off the table straight away. To make sure I interviewed a few students who were sitting down on the seats to see the reason. They were waiting for their next class and were just talking and eating on the tables. The coffee shop downstairs also means other people were sitting at the tables on their laptops enjoying a hot beverage.

So primarily I thought of creating something that could be fast and quick to decipher and understand before the individual moves away from the area. This would bring the same skills across for the Dorset Project I did recently where creating an eye catching design was key. The design would have to be quick to make clear and allow someone who is in a rush to quickly interact with the piece without hardly slowing down or changing their direction. Using a camera based sketch was therefore ideal, as well as using one of the several screens in the room to display the sketch output to make viewing the interaction simple and easy. Before I started brainstorming ideas I made a simple camera sketch.

<code>
import processing.video.*;
Capture cam;
void setup() {
size(640, 480);
cam = new Capture(this,640,480,30);
cam.start();
frameRate(30);
smooth();
//println(Capture.list());
}
void draw(){
if (cam.available()) { 
// Reads the new frame
cam.read(); 
} 
image(cam, 0, 0); 
}
</code>

This allowed me to picture the environment of the space and picture what would go through the minds of the people if they saw previous sketches I have produced on a public screen for all to see. If everyone can see what they see it may not be so intimate and personal. This means I can’t really do anything along those lines as to not offend anyone. I have decided to try and use some sort of tracking to allow the movements of the people as they move through the space react to the sketch. This way I can leave it running and do not have to explain or help anyone, they can choose what to do with the interaction as they wish.

Open cv is a library you can add do Processing, this is done in the sketch tab and can be used to add a lot of information and add sources to your sketch easily and quickly. I have used the video library in the past this is done either through this tab, or by adding something like this at the very top of your sketch.

<center>
<img src="http://www.matthewlean.co.uk/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/sf1.jpg" alt="sf1" width="637" height="477" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-142" />
</center>

<code>
import processing.video.*;
import gab.opencv.*;
</code>

Other libraries include, Kinect , audio and other vision based libraries. These can be used to add devices such as the Kinect or a microphone to the sketch so detect sound and or a 3d depth map. With this information the library makes it easy to add this data to your sketches and play around with the information. This way you can create a depth map that reacts to sound or a sound that starts a video camera and makes it take a screenshot. The list of things you can do is pretty much limitless and is being updated with new libraries every day.

For the openCV library I used it to track my face. After testing the Spider Sketch on my housemates I wanted it to be more dramatic and make it easier to react to more than one person like it would be in the lobby. I didn’t want the experience to be only fixed on one person but make it be available to everyone as they pass the screen. I thought about this and added the spider to the place where the frontal face square is shown. By doing this I replaced the square with the spider image and so whenever the camera reads a frame where the face is shown it will apply the spider to the face. The outcome is quite good however I still need to try and improve some things.

<center>
<img src="http://www.matthewlean.co.uk/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/sf2.jpg" alt="sf2" width="634" height="475" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-143" />
</center>

The image used of the spider is very low quality, this was the same spider used in the previous version of my Spider Sketch. However due to the fact that the spider image would resize depending on the size of the face made it become obvious very quickly that the image was too low resolution. I then went and made a new larger spider image to remove this issue.

<center>
<img src="http://www.matthewlean.co.uk/blog/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/sf3.jpg" alt="sf3" width="637" height="476" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-144" />
</center>

After this I wanted to make the spider have more depth and be more than just a png layered ontop of the face. I decided to give the spider a shadow as this would make its appearance more real and make the png less flat and lifeless. The result is pretty good, as much as the spider does still look fake, the shadow adds some more realism to it.

<center>
[video width="640" height="480" autoplay="autoplay" loop="loop" webm="http://www.matthewlean.co.uk/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/spiderfacewebcam.webm"][/video]
</center>

I finally made the spider a bit bigger to make the spider more apparent when viewed from further away. I did this as when testing the Sketch I couldn’t clearly see it when I was standing 10foot away from the camera. This distance would be the max distance my sketch would properly work on, and it would encourage users further away that are still picked up by the face tracking to come closer and see what was on their face. The code below is the final version of my sketch.

<code>
import processing.video.*;
import gab.opencv.*;
import java.awt.Rectangle;
//
OpenCV opencv;
Capture cam;
Rectangle[] faces;
//
PImage img;
//
void setup() {
size(640, 480,P2D);
img = loadImage("LARGESPIDER2.png");
// Start capturing
cam = new Capture(this, 640, 480);
cam.start();
//
//
opencv = new OpenCV(this, cam.width, cam.height);
//
//
opencv.loadCascade(OpenCV.CASCADE_FRONTALFACE); 
//opencv.loadCascade(OpenCV.CASCADE_EYE); 
//opencv.loadCascade(OpenCV.CASCADE_NOSE); 
}
//
// New images from camera
void captureEvent(Capture cam) {
cam.read();
}
//
void draw() {
//
background(0);
//
opencv.loadImage(cam);
//
faces = opencv.detect();
//
image(cam, 0, 0);
//
if (faces != null) {
for (int i = 0; i < faces.length; i++) {
strokeWeight(2);
stroke(255,0,0);
noFill();
//rect(faces[i].x, faces[i].y, faces[i].width, faces[i].height);
image(img, faces[i].x, faces[i].y, (faces[i].width)*1.2, (faces[i].
height)*1.2); 
}
}
}
